rationale: Source text explicitly states 'The time complexity is O(V + E) where V is vertices and E is edges.'
Source explicitly states BFS uses a queue data structure, not a stack. This directly contradicts the claim.
Source describes BFS basics but doesn't mention cycle detection capabilities. BFS can detect cycles but requires additional tracking mechanisms.
Source text explicitly states 'The time complexity is O(V + E)' for DFS, directly confirming the claim.
Source explicitly states DFS uses recursion or stack, not queue. Queue would implement BFS instead.
DFS explores depth-first, not guaranteeing shortest paths. BFS guarantees shortest paths in unweighted graphs, not DFS.
Source text explicitly states 'Average case time complexity is O(n log n)' which directly confirms the claim.
Source states worst case is O(n^2), not best case. Best case is typically O(n log n).
Source explicitly states quicksort uses O(log n) space for recursion stack, not O(n) auxiliary space.
Source describes quicksort's basic properties but doesn't mention parallelization capabilities or effectiveness when parallelized.
Source explicitly states mergesort has guaranteed O(n log n) time complexity in all cases, confirming worst-case complexity.
Source explicitly states mergesort requires O(n) auxiliary space for merging, contradicting the in-place sorting claim.
Source text explicitly states 'Mergesort is a stable divide-and-conquer algorithm' which directly confirms the claim.
Source explicitly states mergesort uses divide-and-conquer approach, not greedy. These are fundamentally different algorithmic paradigms.
Source explicitly states 'The algorithm works correctly only with non-negative edge weights,' directly confirming the claim.
Source explicitly states Dijkstra's algorithm works correctly only with non-negative edge weights, directly contradicting the claim.
Source describes Dijkstra's mechanics but doesn't explicitly mention dynamic programming. Algorithm does use optimal substructure principles though.
Source explicitly states Bellman-Ford 'can handle negative edge weights and detect negative cycles', directly confirming the claim.
Source explicitly states Bellman-Ford time complexity is O(VE), not O(V^2). The claim contradicts the provided information.
Bellman-Ford relaxes all edges V-1 times systematically, unlike Dijkstra which uses priority queues for vertex selection.
Source text explicitly states 'Time complexity is O(log n)' for binary search, directly confirming the claim.
Source explicitly states binary search requires sorted arrays and works by dividing search intervals, which needs ordering.
Standard binary search finds one occurrence, not all duplicates. Modified versions can find all, but basic algorithm cannot.
Source text explicitly states heapsort has O(n log n) time complexity in all cases, directly confirming the claim.
Source doesn't mention stability. Heapsort is actually unstable, but this cannot be verified from the provided text.
Source text explicitly states counting sort has O(n + k) time complexity where k is range of input values.
Source explicitly states counting sort is 'non-comparison based', directly contradicting the claim that it's comparison-based.
Source text explicitly states radix sort time complexity is O(d(n + k)) where d is number of digits.
Source explicitly states radix sort can process digits from least to most significant OR vice versa, contradicting the claim's 'only' restriction.
Source explicitly states dynamic programming works when problem has optimal substructure, confirming it's a requirement.
Source states dynamic programming stores solutions, which is memoization. Claim incorrectly says it's without memoization.
Source explicitly states greedy algorithms 'don't always produce optimal solutions' directly contradicting the claim they 'always' find optimal solutions.
Source text explicitly states 'It uses a union-find data structure' when describing Kruskal's algorithm.
Source text explicitly states 'Prim's algorithm grows a minimum spanning tree by starting from an arbitrary vertex'.
Source explicitly states topological sorting works on directed acyclic graphs (DAGs), not any directed graph including cyclic ones.
Source explicitly states that push and pop operations both take O(1) time.
Source clearly states stack is Last-In-First-Out (LIFO), not First-In-First-Out (FIFO) as claimed.
Source describes stack operations and uses but doesn't mention implementation methods like linked lists or arrays.
Source explicitly states 'A queue is a First-In-First-Out (FIFO) data structure' which directly confirms the claim.
Source explicitly states elements are removed from the front of a queue, not the rear as claimed.
Source only describes basic FIFO queues, not priority queues. Cannot verify claim about priority queue behavior from provided text.
Source explicitly states that search, insert, and delete operations take O(h) time where h is the height.
Source clearly states left subtree contains values less than the node, not greater than the node.
Source defines BST structure but doesn't explicitly mention inorder traversal or sorted order property during traversal.
Source explicitly states heaps support insert in O(log n) time, directly confirming the claim.
Source clearly states max-heap parents are greater than or equal to children, not less than children.
Heaps support insert and extract-min/max operations in O(log n) time, which are the core operations needed for priority queues.
Source explicitly states hash tables provide average O(1) time for lookup operations, directly confirming the claim.
Source states hash tables provide average O(1) time, not worst-case. Collisions can degrade worst-case performance significantly.
Hash tables use hash functions to map keys to array indices, not sorted order. They prioritize O(1) operations over ordering.
Source explicitly states AVL trees maintain height difference between left and right subtrees of at most 1.
Source explicitly states AVL tree operations take O(log n) time, directly contradicting the claim of O(1) time.

Source explicitly states union-find maintains 'disjoint sets', which by definition are non-overlapping sets that have no elements in common.
